TY  - JOUR
T1  - Simplicity as a Strategy-Making Process: The Effects of Stage of Organizational Development and Environment on Performance
AU  - Lumpkin, G. T.
AU  - Dess, Gregory G.
Y1  - 1995/10/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256862
DO  - 10.5465/256862
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1386
EP  - 1407
VL  - 38
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This field study investigated the importance of simplicity as a strategy-making process. Consistent with our hypotheses, use of a simplistic strategy-making process was found to be positively associated with performance during early stages of organizational development but detrimental to performance as organizations grew and matured. Simplicity was also found to be negatively related to performance in dynamic environments; in heterogeneous environments, it seemed lo be adversely related to performance only in later stages of organizational development.
AB  - This field study investigated the importance of simplicity as a strategy-making process. Consistent with our hypotheses, use of a simplistic strategy-making process was found to be positively associated with performance during early stages of organizational development but detrimental to performance as organizations grew and matured. Simplicity was also found to be negatively related to performance in dynamic environments; in heterogeneous environments, it seemed lo be adversely related to performance only in later stages of organizational development.
