TY  - JOUR
T1  - Job Scope and Stress: Can Job Scope Be Too High?
AU  - Xie, Jia Lin
AU  - Johns, Gary
Y1  - 1995/10/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256858
DO  - 10.5465/256858
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1288
EP  - 1309
VL  - 38
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study examined relationships among job scope, perceived fit between job demands and ability, and stress. Data on scope and stress were provided by 418 full-time employees. Ratings of job complexity from the Dictionary of Occupational Titles (DOT) and the Occupational Prestige Index (OP) also measured job scope. All three job scope measures had a U-shaped curvilinear relationship with emotional exhaustion. Anxiety had a negative association with incumbent-reported job scope but none with the DOT and OP measures. Perceived demands-ability fit moderated the relationship between the DOT and OP measures and stress. People with complex jobs who perceived fit experienced less exhaustion and anxiety than those perceiving misfit.
AB  - This study examined relationships among job scope, perceived fit between job demands and ability, and stress. Data on scope and stress were provided by 418 full-time employees. Ratings of job complexity from the Dictionary of Occupational Titles (DOT) and the Occupational Prestige Index (OP) also measured job scope. All three job scope measures had a U-shaped curvilinear relationship with emotional exhaustion. Anxiety had a negative association with incumbent-reported job scope but none with the DOT and OP measures. Perceived demands-ability fit moderated the relationship between the DOT and OP measures and stress. People with complex jobs who perceived fit experienced less exhaustion and anxiety than those perceiving misfit.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256858
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256858
